                                                   1C<ue5>5C<ue5>McDONALDS<ql>
<styl>by <m0>By PATTY SHILLINGTON<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ep>
<m1><styl>cxon<ql>
<m2> <ql>
<m0>   At Bayfront Park on Thursday, the world's top fast-food chain that has successfully snagged millions of loyal burger-eating, playground-loving kids courted a different market: downtown Miami's yuppie lunch crowd.<ep>
 <m1><styl>cxoff<ql>
<m0>  Here and across the United States and Canada, in the most elaborate product introduction in its history, McDonald's debuted its Arch Deluxe sandwich, a fat-rich, premium-priced bacon cheeseburger ``with a grown-up taste'' that the fast-food giant hopes will boost sales among the nation's 78 million baby boomers.<ep>
   ``We've always appealed to families and children,'' said Larry DeVries, McDonald's Boca Raton-based vice president who oversaw Thursday's festive giveaway of more than 1,000 Arch Deluxes and canned sodas. ``We felt we needed to do a little more for adult consumers.''<ep>
   And what better cultural icon to seduce the adult consumer with a discriminating palate and pocketbook than . . . a red-nosed, floppy-shoed clown?<ep>
   As part of the Oak Brook, Ill.-based company's marketing scheme, Ronald McDonald has suddenly matured (--) in behavior, if not fashion sense. In recent TV commercials, Ronald plays golf with the guys, shoots billiards in a pool hall, dances at a nightclub.<ep>
   Thursday, Ronald McDonald donned a hamburger-patterned tie and black-suit jacket to push the Arch Deluxe. ``Ronald's been around for so long he can appeal to people who used to love him when they were small,'' DeVries said.<ep>
   Consider this another battle in the Burger Wars. One that recognizes an aging population and a saturated kiddie market, say restaurant analysts.<ep>
   The fast-food market is ardently competitive, increasingly crowded and, at $50 billion, so massive that even tiny sales victories can translate <m2><ql>
<ql>
