McDONALDS,  FROM  1C<ql>
<m0>into big bucks. McDonald's domestic share of that market rose 0.6 percent last year to 42.3 percent, said Ron Paul, president of Technomic Inc., a food industry research and consulting firm in Chicago.<ep>
   But most of that growth came from new stores rather than increased business at existing stores.<ep>
   Miami-based Burger King, McDonald's closest competitor, also gained a 0.6 percent market share last year, up to 18.2 percent.<ep>
   But sales at Burger King's existing stores are way up (--) 12.9 percent in the past two years, company spokeswoman Kim Miller said Thursday.<ep>
   ``McDonald's has got to get current customers to come back more frequently or attract some of their competitors' customers if this is going to work,'' said Paul. ``I think they have all pretty well mined the children's market.''<ep>
   Miller called McDonald's Arch Deluxe marketing campaign ``a reaction to our success.'' About a month ago, Burger King launched a new series of commercials touting specific menu items. ``The idea is to bring customers back into the restaurant,'' she said.<ep>
   In the end, of course, it will be fast-food consumers, a tough lot, who decide whether the Arch Deluxe will succeed or go the way of McDonald's defunct, low-fat McLean Deluxe, which did not catch on despite a health-conscious public and intense marketing.<ep>
   In Bayfront Park, people lined up in the midday sun to try out the Arch Deluxe. They had in common perhaps only one thing: the appetite for a free lunch.<ep>
   ``I don't really understand the concept of this `grown-up taste,' '' said Jairo Arzt, a 22-year-old student at Miami-Dade Community College's Wolfson Campus. He said the Arch Deluxe reminded him of Wendy's hamburgers. ``If it's more than $2, it's not worth it.''<ep>
   Sorry, Jairo, but the Arch Deluxe may cost up to $3 in some markets.<ep>
   And he doesn't buy a grown-up Ronald McDonald. ``It's confusing the public,'' Arzt said. ``They want to cater to all markets but the children will feel neglected and the adults won't get it. It's a mistake.''<ep>
   Other adults like Greg Stewart remember Ronald from their childhood and said they still identify with him and find the new TV commercials fun and effective.<ep>
   Jacob Dorn, 51, who works for Metro-Dade County's real estate office, said ``a free lunch will usually draw me in,'' but hey, it's still just a hamburger.<ep>
   ``We're not talking asparagus and hollandaise here,'' he said. ``Without a significant menu change, I don't see how they're going to capture an additional large percentage of the market.''<ep>
   Nick DeBellis, 22, considers himself a burger connoisseur and really liked the Arch Deluxe. But one thing is still missing, he said.<ep>
   ``Now all McDonald's needs to do is serve beer.''<ep>
